snippet.textDisplay: When these hospital ships were first launched during the Cold War, their purpose WERE to be deployed to war zones. Their dimensions and home bases also tells us many things about the U.S.'s strategies at the time. The Navy only built two because they only anticipated simultaneous action on at most two fronts: The Pacific and Europe. This anticipation also sheds light on why one ship is based in San Diego (Pacific), while the other is based at Norfolk (Europe). Meanwhile, the ships' capacities represent an estimation of the first wave casualties after engaging the enemy: Around 1,000. Of course, a war with the Soviet Union never took place, which is why they were never actually deployed for their original purposes.

snippet.textDisplay:
It seems like, given the functional requirements, a purpose-built hospital ship should be a very large SWATH hull with the ability to raise the submerged hulls and operate as a catamaran.


As a subtype of catamaran, one of the features of such a ship is a very large deck area relative to it's size.
And of course, conventional catamarans are amongst the fastest type of ships, often capable of operating in the 80-100km/h speed range or higher, making for rapid deployment capability.
However, a conventional catamaran is not known for it's stability.
The SWATH design however, is purpose built for being as stable as platform as is reasonably possible for a floating structure.
Thus, such a design would be able to deploy quickly as a catamaran, switch to SWATH mode at it's destination, thus providing as stable a platform as possible.

The downside to a SWATH design is that it's fairly high maintenance and can't carry a heavy load.
But, since this would be a floating hospital, not a cargo ship, that shouldn't be a major issue overall...


Still, I can see why that kind of design isn't all that likely to be built...


But it's interesting to think about...

snippet.textDisplay: I worked on the USNS Comfort so was curious how they depicted it in this video.First of all the ship isnt for fast action deployments but as a contingency for humanitarian reasons eg Phillipines,Haiti,Africa etc.The purpose is the same as what is being used in NEW YORK not for COVID19 but for overflow of "other" cases to reduce the workload for the Doctors doing Covid 19 cases.Contingency not field operations was one mistake of the video.The other is the crew is entirely civilian Merchant seaman called"Civmars"they are federal civilian Merchant Mariners that work for the DOD with a Master in charge of the vessel.Second error is the USNS Comfort is not out of Norfolk but out of Baltimore.
